2024-02-01 - Resolving Leaflet issue on macOS

Metadata card
  • Diary entry date: 01 February 2024
  • MS5130 learning outcomes:
    • #3. Install and exploit open source statistical programming packages.
    • #5. Create relevant visualisations using advanced statistical programming plotting packages.
  • MS5130 learning activities:
    • MS5130 Week 04 lecture
    • Work contributing to MS5130 Assignment 1

Problem statement:

When attempting to run R code that calls on the leaflet package, the following error occurred as per FigureÂ 1 below:

Solution statement:

In order to investigate further, I scrolled through the console output in RStudio. The following part of the console output drew my attention, even though I do not fully understand it, as depicted in FigureÂ 2 below.

I have never heard of gdal-config before, so I performed a Google search for âgdal-configâ, which directed me to Stack Overflow #12141422:

One of the posts on that thread, #57986572, suggested that it is necessary on macOS to install gdal at the level of the operating system, using Homebrew, i.e., brew install gdal. I therefore performed that step; however, I then received a similar error message about proj missing, which prompted me to perform a similar search about proj, taking me to Stack Overflow #30034372, which advised me to similarly install proj using Homebrew. So, I performed the following overall installation of packages using Homebrew:

brew install gdal proj

At this stage, however, I continued to experience problems with Leaflet in RStudio even though I installed the required underlying packages. The error message that I received was as follows: âerror: libproj or sqlite3 not found in standard or given locationsâ.

I performed a Google Search for that exact error message, which took me to a discussion thread on GitHub, #1894 on r-spatial/sf. The solution was revealed by the user pat-s (see their comment here), who advised a customised version of install.packages(...) in RStudio, as follows:

install.packages("terra", type = "source", configure.args = c("--with-sqlite3-lib=/opt/homebrew/opt/sqlite/lib", "--with-proj-lib=/opt/homebrew/opt/proj/lib"))

install.packages("leaflet", type = "source", configure.args = c("--with-sqlite3-lib=/opt/homebrew/opt/sqlite/lib", "--with-proj-lib=/opt/homebrew/opt/proj/lib"))

Now, once I performed all required steps in both Homebrew and RStudio, it all works!

To contribute to the open-source community using Leaflet in Quarto/RStudio, I made my findings available to the public on GitHub here: https://github.com/blairw/docs-leaflet-rstudio-macos
